Axiom Summaries (Reference)

1. Ecology Defines the Boundary

BIO issuance may occur only where ecological continuity can be truthfully witnessed.

Land area therefore defines the outer spatial boundary of issuance.

Axiom:
No ecology, no issuance surface.

⸻

2. Cells Bound the Issuance Surface

Issuance is possible only within declared ecological cells whose boundaries are immutable.

Expansion requires new polygons and independent witnessing.

Axiom:
Issuance expands only by adding new exposure surfaces.

⸻

3. Human Presence Bounds Observation

Ecological truth must remain falsifiable.

The Human Presence Constant ensures that witnessing capacity cannot exceed real human time present.

Axiom:
Time spent watching is the upper limit of what may be claimed.

⸻

4. Seasons Bound State Transitions

BIO issuance may occur only at ecological seasonal endpoints following completed stress windows.

This prevents continuous or discretionary issuance.

Axiom:
Ecological time advances in seasons, not transactions.

⸻

5. Protection Gates Time

If Protection fails, ecological time accounting collapses.

No issuance can occur during disturbance or entropy acceleration.

Axiom:
Only protected time may be recorded.

⸻

6. Regeneration Requires Direction

Protection preserves continuity.

Regeneration requires directional improvement in ecological energy capture and community dynamics.

Axiom:
Endurance preserves truth. Regeneration proves it.

⸻

7. Difficulty Tightens With Success

As ecosystems mature, regenerative claims become harder to justify.

The Ecological Difficulty Adjustment raises proof thresholds.

Axiom:
The longer truth survives, the harder it becomes to claim more.

⸻

8. Issuance Is Front-Weighted

The highest issuance occurs during early exposure when uncertainty and risk are greatest.

Later issuance declines as ecological integrity stabilises.

Axiom:
Maximum issuance occurs at maximum exposure.

⸻

9. Finance Cannot Expand Issuance

Market demand, funding pressure, or governance preference cannot increase issuance.

BIO absorbs financial stress while BDR remains indifferent.

Axiom:
Money adapts to ecology. Ecology never adapts to money.

⸻

10. The Maximum Envelope Emerges Naturally

The maximum issuance envelope emerges from three constraints:
	•	ecological surface area (cells)
	•	real human observation time (HPC)
	•	ecological difficulty tightening (EDA)

It is therefore discovered rather than decided.

Axiom:
Issuance is bounded by land, time, and difficulty.

⸻

